# DataStatistics Architecture Rule

Use this stack and structure for all new work in this repository:
- Backend: latest .NET ASP.NET Web API, Ocelot gateway, GraphQL for FE access.
- Messaging: RabbitMQ is mandatory for inter-service data flow.
- Frontend: Angular + GraphQL client; real-time updates via SignalR/WebSockets.
- Persistence: relational or document DB with migration scripts and seeded local setup.

# Onion Layering (mandatory)

Every backend service follows: `Data -> Service -> Application -> Abstractions + Shared`.
- `Data`: EF Core/repositories/external providers only, no business orchestration.
- `Service`: domain and orchestration logic, queue/event handlers, validation coordination.
- `Application`: HTTP/GraphQL endpoints, DTO mapping, request/response contracts.
- `Abstractions`: interfaces and contracts for cross-layer dependencies.
- `Shared`: shared primitives, result/error models, logging/telemetry helpers.

# Service Responsibilities

- Data Ingestor: poll WeakApp with resilient retries/backoff, publish normalized messages to RabbitMQ.
- Data Processor: consume queue messages idempotently, persist raw + aggregated data.
- Gateway API: expose FE-focused REST + GraphQL endpoints with filtering/pagination/aggregations.
- Notification service: publish live updates to clients through SignalR/WebSockets.

# Engineering Guardrails

- Add structured logging and explicit error handling in every boundary (API, queue, DB, external API).
- Add unit tests for logic and integration tests for queue + DB + API paths.
- Every service and FE must include CI workflow: lint, test, build, Docker image build.
- Keep PRs small and reviewable; use feature branches and PR-only merges.

# Definition of Done (for each feature)

- Works in local `docker-compose` with WeakApp + RabbitMQ + DB + all services + frontend.
- GraphQL schema is strongly typed and supports filtering, pagination, and aggregations.
- UI shows latest data, charts, location/type aggregations, loading/error states, and live updates.
